    <div class="explanation">
        <h2>Algorithm Complexities</h2>
        <p><strong>Bubble Sort:</strong> Time Complexity: O(n²) (worst and average cases) | Space Complexity: O(1). It's simple but inefficient for large datasets as it repeatedly swaps adjacent elements until sorted.</p>
        <p><strong>Quick Sort:</strong> Time Complexity: Average O(n log n), Worst O(n²) | Space Complexity: O(log n). It uses a divide-and-conquer approach by selecting a pivot and partitioning the array, making it generally very fast in practice.</p>
        <p><strong>Merge Sort:</strong> Time Complexity: O(n log n) (always) | Space Complexity: O(n). It divides the array into halves, sorts them, and merges them back, ensuring consistent performance but using extra space.</p>
        <p>In summary, while Bubble Sort works for small or nearly sorted arrays, Quick Sort and Merge Sort are better for most cases due to their efficiency with larger datasets.</p>
