            <li><strong>In Larger Applications:</strong> Singletons work well for simple, global states like themes in a small demo, but in scalable apps, DI allows for dependency management without global state, reducing coupling and improving maintainability.</li>
            <li><strong>When Flexibility is Needed:</strong> If you anticipate multiple theme managers (e.g., per user session), alternatives like the Factory pattern can create instances dynamically. Use DI when you want to pass configurations or themes as parameters, avoiding hard-coded global access.</li>
            <li><strong>Best Practices:</strong> Consider DI frameworks (e.g., in Angular or React with context/providers) for modern web apps, as they promote loose coupling and easier debugging compared to Singletons.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>In summary, while Singletons are simple for this demo, they're best used sparingly. For production-level code, evaluate trade-offs and opt for DI when dealing with dependencies that could change or need isolation.</p>
