                <p>As in this example, cap the recursion depth (e.g., via the slider) and switch to an iterative method for deeper levels. For instance, if you need to go beyond depth 12, you could draw the initial levels recursively and then use a loop for the rest. This is useful in graphics rendering, where you might limit recursion to 5–10 levels and approximate the rest with precomputed patterns.</p></li>

            <li><strong>Implement Tail Recursion Optimization (if available)</strong>: 
                <p>In tail-recursive functions (where the recursive call is the last operation), some languages (like Scheme or functional languages) can optimize the code to reuse the same stack frame, preventing overflows. JavaScript doesn't natively support this, but you can use libraries or transpile code (e.g., with Babel) to achieve similar effects. For fractals, refactor the function to be tail-recursive if possible, though it's not straightforward here.</p></li>

            <li><strong>Increase Stack Size (Environment-Specific)</strong>: 
                <p>In some environments, you can manually increase the stack size. For example, in Node.js, use the `--stack-size` flag when running scripts. In C++ or Java, adjust VM settings. However, this is a temporary fix and doesn't address the root problem—it might lead to other issues like excessive memory use. For web apps like this, it's often not feasible due to browser limitations.</p></li>

            <li><strong>Use Asynchronous or Generator-Based Recursion</strong>: 
                <p>For very deep recursions, break the process into smaller chunks using generators (in JavaScript) or asynchronous functions. For example, yield control after each level and resume later, preventing the stack from growing too large. In a fractal generator, you could create a function that yields branch data one level at a time, allowing the browser to handle it without blocking. This is particularly useful in real-time applications, like AI-driven simulations, to avoid freezing the UI.</p></li>

            <li><strong>Memoization and Dynamic Programming for Related Problems</strong>: 
                <p>While not directly applicable to pure fractals, for recursive algorithms with overlapping subproblems (e.g., Fibonacci or pathfinding), memoization caches results to reduce calls. This indirectly helps with depth by making the recursion faster and less resource-intensive. In fractals, you could memoize branch positions if rendering the same structure multiple times.</p></li>
        </ol>
