    <h1>Race Condition Counter Demonstration</h1>
    <div class="container">
        <div class="counter-section" id="buggy-section">
            <h2>Buggy Counter</h2>
            <p id="buggyCount">0</p>
            <button id="buggyButton">Increment (Buggy)</button>
            <p>This version has a race condition. Rapid clicks trigger overlapping <code>setTimeout</code> calls that read, modify, and write a shared counter variable asynchronously. This can cause the count to display incorrect values, as updates may overwrite each other.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="counter-section" id="fixed-section">
            <h2>Fixed Counter</h2>
            <p id="fixedCount">0</p>
            <button id="fixedButton">Increment (Fixed)</button>
            <p>This version uses a lock to prevent overlapping updates. Even with rapid clicks, the counter ensures that only one update processes at a time, avoiding lost increments.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explanation">
        <h3>Explanation of the Race Condition and Fix</h3>
        <p><strong>Race Condition in Buggy Version:</strong> In the buggy counter, each button click schedules a <code>setTimeout</code> function that asynchronously reads the current count, increments it, and writes it back. If you click the button rapidly, multiple <code>setTimeout</code> calls may overlap. For example, if the count is 0, two quick clicks might both read 0, increment it to 1, and write 1 back—resulting in the final count being 1 instead of 2. This happens because the operations are not atomic, leading to lost updates and incorrect values.</p>

        <p><strong>Fix in Fixed Version:</strong> To resolve this, a simple lock (a boolean flag) is used to ensure that only one update can be scheduled at a time. If an update is already in progress, additional clicks are ignored until the current one completes. This serializes the updates, preventing overlaps and ensuring the counter always reflects the correct value. In a real-world scenario, you might use more robust synchronization like promises, mutexes, or a queue for better handling.</p>

        <p><strong>How to Test:</strong> Click the "Increment (Buggy)" button rapidly (e.g., 5-10 times quickly) and observe the displayed count—it may not match the number of clicks. Then, do the same with the "Increment (Fixed)" button; it should accurately reflect the clicks.</p>
    </div>

    <script>
        // Buggy Counter Implementation
        let buggyCount = 0;  // Shared counter variable
        const buggyButton = document.getElementById('buggyButton');
        const buggyCountDisplay = document.getElementById('buggyCount');

        buggyButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
            setTimeout(() => {
                let temp = buggyCount;  // Read the current value
                temp++;                  // Modify it
                buggyCount = temp;       // Write it back
                buggyCountDisplay.textContent = buggyCount;  // Update display
            }, 0);  // Asynchronous delay
        });

        // Fixed Counter Implementation
        let fixedCount = 0;  // Shared counter variable
        let isFixedUpdating = false;  // Lock flag
        const fixedButton = document.getElementById('fixedButton');
        const fixedCountDisplay = document.getElementById('fixedCount');

        fixedButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
            if (!isFixedUpdating) {  // Check if an update is in progress
                isFixedUpdating = true;  // Acquire the lock
                setTimeout(() => {
                    fixedCount++;  // Directly increment (no reading inside timeout)
                    fixedCountDisplay.textContent = fixedCount;  // Update display
                    isFixedUpdating = false;  // Release the lock
                }, 0);  // Asynchronous delay, but with locking
            }
            // If isFixedUpdating is true, this click is ignored to prevent overlap
        });
    </script>
