    <p>This version attempts to draw the Fibonacci spiral but fails because the starting point for each arc is not updated correctly. As a result, all arcs are drawn from the same center, leading to overlapping concentric circles instead of a proper spiral.</p>
    <canvas id="buggyCanvas"></canvas>

    <h2>Corrected Version (Proper Spiral)</h2>
    <p>This version correctly updates the starting point for each arc based on the end point of the previous one, resulting in a proper Fibonacci spiral where each arc's radius is a Fibonacci number.</p>
    <canvas id="correctCanvas"></canvas>

    <h2>Explanation of the Bug</h2>
    <p>
        The real bug in the buggy version is a mishandling of the base cases for positioning the arcs. In a proper Fibonacci spiral, each arc should be drawn at the end point of the previous arc to form an outward spiral pattern. However, in the buggy version, the code does not update the center point after drawing each arc. Instead, it always starts from the initial center, causing all subsequent arcs to overlap at the same location.

        Specifically:
        - Fibonacci sequence used: [1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, 21] (generated starting from the standard base cases).
        - In the buggy code, the center coordinates (<code>cx</code> and <code>cy</code>) are not modified after each arc, leading to concentric drawing.
        - In the corrected code, the center is updated to the end point of the current arc, which ensures the spiral expands correctly.

        This issue might stem from an oversight in the original code's base case for the drawing loop, such as forgetting to account for the cumulative position offsets required for the spiral's geometry. To fix it, we simply add the logic to calculate and update the new center based on the arc's end point.
