<body>
    <h1>Why Bubble Sort Isn't the Best for All Use Cases</h1>

    <div id="explanation">
        <p><strong>Bubble Sort:</strong> This algorithm repeatedly compares and swaps adjacent elements. Its time complexity is O(n²) in the average and worst cases, making it inefficient for large datasets.</p>
        <p><strong>Quick Sort:</strong> This divide-and-conquer algorithm selects a pivot and partitions the array. Its average time complexity is O(n log n), but it can degrade to O(n²) in the worst case (e.g., already sorted data).</p>
        <p><strong>Merge Sort:</strong> This divide-and-conquer algorithm divides the array into halves, sorts them, and merges them back. It has a consistent time complexity of O(n log n), making it efficient and stable for most scenarios.</p>
        <p>This demonstration shows these algorithms sorting the same randomized array side by side. Notice how Bubble Sort takes more steps compared to the others, especially for larger arrays.</p>
    </div>

    <div id="visualization">
        <div class="algorithm-container">
            <h2>Bubble Sort</h2>
            <div id="bubble-chart" class="bar-chart"></div>
