        </div>

        <h2>Explanation of SQL Injection and Why Parameterized Queries Are Safe</h2>
        <p>
            SQL injection is a security vulnerability that occurs when user input is directly incorporated into a database query without proper sanitization. In this demo:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Vulnerable Mode:</strong> We simulate this by using the user's input directly to construct a regular expression for filtering. For example, if you enter "<code>.*</code>", it matches all products because it's a valid regex pattern that means "anything". This demonstrates how an attacker could manipulate the query to return unintended results, similar to how <code>' OR '1'='1</code> could bypass filters in real SQL.</li>
            <li><strong>Safe Mode:</strong> We use a parameterized approach (e.g., checking if the product name includes the search term as a literal string). This ensures the input is treated as data, not code, preventing any manipulation. In real databases, this is achieved using prepared statements or parameterized queries, which separate the query structure from the user input.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            <strong>Why is this safe?</strong> Parameterized queries prevent injection by ensuring that user input is never executed as part of the query logic. Instead, it's passed as a value to be compared or filtered against. This separation makes it impossible for attackers to alter the query's structure, protecting against common exploits like returning all records or deleting data.
        </p>
