    <h2>Discussion on the Singleton Pattern</h2>
    <p><strong>Pros of the Singleton Pattern:</strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Global Access:</strong> It provides a single point of access to an instance, making it easy to manage shared resources like the theme state in this example. This ensures consistency across the application without needing to pass the object around.</li>
        <li><strong>Resource Efficiency:</strong> By guaranteeing only one instance exists, it can prevent unnecessary object creation, which is useful for scenarios involving expensive resources (e.g., database connections or configuration managers).</li>
        <li><strong>Simplicity for Configuration:</strong> In applications like this theme toggler, it's straightforward to use a Singleton for global settings, as it centralizes control and avoids duplication.</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Cons of the Singleton Pattern:</strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Global State Issues:</strong> Singletons introduce global state, which can lead to tight coupling between parts of the code. This makes the application harder to test, debug, and maintain, as changes in one place can unexpectedly affect others.</li>
        <li><strong>Testing Challenges:</strong> It's difficult to mock or replace a Singleton during unit testing, which can result in brittle tests. For instance, in this demo, you'd have to reset the theme state manually for each test.</li>
        <li><strong>Scalability Problems:</strong> In larger applications, Singletons can create hidden dependencies, making the codebase less modular and harder to extend. They also aren't inherently thread-safe in multi-threaded environments (though JavaScript is single-threaded, this is still a concern in other languages).</li>
        <li><strong>Violation of Single Responsibility Principle:</strong> Over time, a Singleton might accumulate too many responsibilities, bloating the class and violating clean code principles.</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>When is Dependency Injection a Better Choice?</strong></p>
    <p>Dependency Injection (DI) is often preferable when you want to avoid the pitfalls of global state and make your code more flexible, testable, and maintainable. Instead of relying on a Singleton to provide a global instance, DI involves passing dependencies (like a theme manager) explicitly to the components that need them.</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Improved Modularity:</strong> DI allows you to swap out implementations easily. For example, you could inject a different theme manager for testing or for different environments, without affecting the rest of the app.</li>
        <li><strong>Better Testability:</strong> With DI, you can mock dependencies in tests, making it easier to isolate and verify components. In this theme toggle example, you could inject a mock theme manager to simulate theme changes without altering global state.</li>
        <li><strong>Reduced Coupling:</strong> DI promotes loose coupling by explicitly defining dependencies, which makes the code more reusable and easier to refactor. For instance, if you were building a larger web app, you could inject the theme manager into specific components rather than having it globally accessible.</li>
        <li><strong>When to Choose DI Over Singleton:</strong> Use DI in scenarios where flexibility is key, such as in modular applications, frameworks like Angular or React with context/providers, or when dealing with multiple instances (e.g., different themes per user session). If your app needs to be scalable, testable, or support features like A/B testing, DI is generally a better fit than Singleton.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>In summary, while the Singleton works well for simple, global state management like this demo, Dependency Injection is often recommended for more complex applications to enhance maintainability and avoid common pitfalls.</p>

    <script>
        // Singleton Pattern Implementation for Theme Management
        var ThemeManager = (function() {
            var instance;  // Private instance

            function createInstance() {
                var theme = 'light';  // Default theme

                return {
                    getTheme: function() {
                        return theme;
                    },
                    setTheme: function(newTheme) {
                        theme = newTheme;  // Update the theme
                        applyTheme();  // Apply the theme to the page
                    }
                };
            }

            return {
                getInstance: function() {
                    if (!instance) {
                        instance = createInstance();  // Create if it doesn't exist
                    }
                    return instance;
                }
            };
        })();

        // Function to apply the theme to elements
        function applyTheme() {
            var themeManager = ThemeManager.getInstance();
            var currentTheme = themeManager.getTheme();

            // Update the body class to apply the theme
            document.body.className = currentTheme;

            // Optionally, update specific elements (though body class cascades here)
            var elements = document.querySelectorAll('h1, p, #content, button');
            elements.forEach(function(element) {
                element.className = currentTheme;  // Add theme class to each element
            });
        }

        // Event listener for the toggle button
        document.getElementById('toggleBtn').addEventListener('click', function() {
            var themeManager = ThemeManager.getInstance();
            var currentTheme = themeManager.getTheme();
            var newTheme = currentTheme === 'light' ? 'dark' : 'light';  // Toggle theme
            themeManager.setTheme(newTheme);
        });

        // Initialize the theme on page load
        applyTheme();
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

