    <div class="explanation">
        <h2>Limitations of Regex for Email Validation</h2>
        <p>While regular expressions (like the one used above) can check for a basic email format, they cannot fully validate email addresses as per the official specifications in RFC 5322. This RFC defines a wide range of valid email formats, including:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Quoted strings (e.g., "john.doe"@example.com)</li>
            <li>Comments and folding white space (e.g., john.doe(comment)@example.com)</li>
            <li>Internationalized domain names and special characters</li>
            <li>Complex structures that go beyond simple patterns</li>
        </ul>
        <p>As a result, a regex might incorrectly flag some valid emails as invalid or vice versa, making it unreliable for comprehensive validation. This is because regex is designed for pattern matching, not for parsing the full complexity of email standards.</p>

        <h3>Practical Alternatives for Production Use</h3>
        <p>For more robust email validation in real-world applications, consider the following alternatives:</p>
