        <h2>Discussion: Pros and Cons of the Singleton Pattern</h2>
        <p>The singleton pattern is used in this demo to manage the theme state. It ensures that only one instance of the theme manager exists, providing a global point of access for theme-related operations.</p>

        <h3>Pros of the Singleton Pattern:</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Global Access:</strong> It allows easy access to the theme state from anywhere in the application without passing instances around, which simplifies code in smaller projects.</li>
            <li><strong>Lazy Initialization:</strong> The instance is created only when first needed, which can improve performance by delaying resource allocation.</li>
            <li><strong>Controlled Access:</strong> It restricts the creation of multiple instances, ensuring consistency in state management (e.g., only one theme state is maintained).</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Cons of the Singleton Pattern:</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Tight Coupling:</strong> Code that uses the singleton becomes dependent on its global instance, making it harder to modify or test in isolation.</li>
            <li><strong>Global State Issues:</strong> Singletons can lead to hidden dependencies and make debugging difficult, as changes in one part of the app can unexpectedly affect others.</li>
            <li><strong>Not Thread-Safe in All Environments:</strong> In multi-threaded scenarios (e.g., some server-side contexts), ensuring only one instance is created can be challenging.</li>
            <li><strong>Reduced Flexibility:</strong> It's hard to extend or replace the singleton in larger applications, as it's essentially a global variable in disguise.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>When Are Alternatives Like Dependency Injection Better?</h3>
        <p>While singletons work well for simple scenarios like this theme manager, alternatives such as dependency injection (DI) are preferable in more complex applications. DI involves passing dependencies (e.g., the theme manager) explicitly to components that need them, rather than relying on global access.</p>
        <p><strong>Reasons to Use Dependency Injection Instead:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Improved Modularity and Testability:</strong> DI makes it easier to swap out implementations (e.g., for unit testing with mock objects) without altering the code that uses it, reducing tight coupling.</li>
            <li><strong>Flexibility in Larger Apps:</strong> In scalable projects, DI allows for better management of dependencies, enabling features like configuration-based instantiation or handling multiple instances (e.g., per-user themes).</li>
            <li><strong>Avoiding Global State:</strong> DI promotes cleaner architecture by explicitly defining dependencies, which helps prevent bugs from unintended global interactions and makes the code more maintainable.</li>
            <li><strong>Best for Frameworks and Libraries:</strong> In modern web development (e.g., with React, Angular, or Vue), DI is often built-in and preferred for managing services, as it aligns with principles like inversion of control.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>In summary, use singletons for straightforward, global needs in small-scale code, but opt for DI when building robust, testable, and extensible applications to avoid the pitfalls of global state.</p>
    </section>

    <script>
        // Singleton Pattern for Theme Management
        const ThemeManager = (function() {
            let instance;  // Private instance

            function createInstance() {
                let theme = 'light';  // Private state for the current theme

                return {
                    getTheme: function() {
