    <div class="explanation">
        <h2>Why Regex Can't Fully Validate Email Addresses</h2>
        <p>Regex (regular expressions) is often used for basic email validation, but it has significant limitations when it comes to fully adhering to the official email specifications defined in RFC 5322 (and earlier versions like RFC 2822 or RFC 822). Here's why:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Complexity of the RFC rules:</strong> The RFC specifications allow for a wide range of valid email formats, including quoted strings, comments (e.g., in parentheses), international characters, and complex domain structures. A simple regex can't capture all these edge cases without becoming extremely long and brittle.</li>
            <li><strong>Practical vs. theoretical validation:</strong> While regex can check for a basic structure (e.g., something@something.something), it doesn't verify if the email actually exists or is deliverable. For instance, an email like "pretty much anything"@example.com is technically valid under RFC but would likely fail in real-world use.</li>
            <li><strong>Edge cases and internationalization:</strong> Emails can include Unicode characters, IP addresses in domains, or even quoted local parts (e.g., "john doe"@example.com). Most regex patterns overlook these, leading to false positives or negatives.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Suggested Alternatives for Production Use:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Use dedicated libraries:</strong> In JavaScript, libraries like <a href="https://github.com/validatorjs/validator.js" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">validator.js</a> provide more robust email validation functions that go beyond simple regex. On the server-side, Python's <code>email_validator</code> library or PHP's built-in filters can be more reliable.</li>
            <li><strong>Server-side verification:</strong> Don't rely solely on client-side validation. Perform full checks on the server, such as querying DNS for MX records (to confirm the domain can receive email) or even sending a confirmation email to the address.</li>
            <li><strong>API services:</strong> Integrate with external services like ZeroBounce, NeverBounce, or Abstract's email validation APIs, which can check for syntax, domain validity, and even disposable email addresses.</li>
            <li><strong>Best practice:</strong> Combine multiple methods—use regex for quick client-side feedback, but always validate thoroughly on the server to ensure security and accuracy.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>In summary, while regex is useful for a quick sanity check, it's not a substitute for proper email validation in production environments. Always prioritize user experience and security by using comprehensive tools.</p>
    </div>

