- Clear explanations: At the top and bottom, I'll include text explaining the concepts, including why parameterized queries are safer.

This demo is simplified for educational purposes and runs entirely in the browser using JavaScript. It doesn't connect to a real database or execute real SQL, but it illustrates the principles.

Here's the complete HTML file. You can copy and paste it into a text editor, save it as `sql_injection_demo.html`, and open it in a web browser to try it out.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>SQL Injection Demo: Vulnerable vs. Safe Search</title>
    <style>
        body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; margin: 20px; }
        .container { max-width: 800px; margin: auto; }
        .section { margin-bottom: 20px; }
        .input-group { margin-bottom: 10px; }
        button { padding: 10px; margin-right: 10px; }
        .results { border: 1px solid #ccc; padding: 10px; background-color: #f9f9f9; }
        .error { color: red; }
        .success { color: green; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>SQL Injection Demo: Vulnerable vs. Safe Search</h1>

        <div class="section">
            <p>This demo simulates a product search on a mock in-memory database. It has two modes:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Vulnerable Mode (String Concatenation)</strong>: This directly incorporates your input into a query string, which can lead to injection attacks. For example, if you input something like "1 || true", it might return all results unexpectedly.</li>
                <li><strong>Safe Mode (Parameterized Filtering)</strong>: This treats your input as data only, preventing injection by not allowing it to alter the query structure.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Try entering normal values (e.g., "1") or injection attempts (e.g., "1 || true") to see the difference. The database is an array of products with IDs as numbers.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="section input-group">
            <label for="searchInput">Enter search term (e.g., a product ID value):</label>
            <input type="text" id="searchInput" placeholder="e.g., 1 or '1 || true'">

            <label for="searchMode">Select Search Mode:</label>
            <select id="searchMode">
                <option value="vulnerable">Vulnerable (String Concatenation)</option>
                <option value="safe">Safe (Parameterized Filtering)</option>
            </select>

            <button id="searchButton">Perform Search</button>
        </div>

        <div class="section results" id="results">
            <h3>Search Results:</h3>
            <p id="resultsText">No search performed yet.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>Explanation of Results</h2>
            <p>When you perform a search, the code filters a mock database based on the selected mode. Here's what happens:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Vulnerable Mode</strong>: The input is directly concatenated into a JavaScript expression, simulating how SQL injection works in real code. For example, if you input "1 || true", the filter might evaluate to always true, returning all products. This demonstrates how attackers can manipulate queries to access unintended data.</li>
                <li><strong>Safe Mode</strong>: The input is treated as pure data (e.g., parsed as a number for ID search). Even if you input "1 || true", it's not interpreted as code, so the filter only checks for an exact ID match (e.g., 1), ignoring any "extra" parts. This prevents injection.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Why Parameterized Queries Work:</strong> In real-world databases, parameterized queries (or prepared statements) separate code from data. The database engine treats user input as values, not as part of the query logic. This means even if an attacker tries to inject malicious code (like SQL keywords), it can't alter the query structure—it's just treated as literal data. For example, in a real SQL query, you'd use something like: <code>SELECT * FROM products WHERE id = ?</code> and pass the value separately, rather than concatenating strings like <code>SELECT * FROM products WHERE id = ' + userInput + '</code>. This practice is essential for security and should always be used in production code.</p>
        </div>

        <script>
            // Mock in-memory database: An array of product objects
            const database = [
                { id: 1, name: "Laptop", description: "A powerful computing device" },
                { id: 2, name: "Phone", description: "A mobile communication device" },
                { id: 3, name: "Tablet", description: "A portable entertainment device" },
                { id: 4, name: "Monitor", description: "A high-resolution display" }
            ];

            const searchInput = document.getElementById('searchInput');
            const searchMode = document.getElementById('searchMode');
            const searchButton = document.getElementById('searchButton');
            const resultsText = document.getElementById('resultsText');

            searchButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
                const input = searchInput.value.trim();
                const mode = searchMode.value;
                let results = [];
                let message = '';

                if (input === '') {
                    resultsText.innerHTML = '<p class="error">Please enter a search term.</p>';
                    return;
                }

                if (mode === 'vulnerable') {
                    // Vulnerable mode: Concatenate input directly into a JavaScript expression
                    // This simulates string concatenation in SQL queries
                    try {
                        results = database.filter(item => eval(`item.id ${input}`));  // e.g., if input is "== 1 || true", it evaluates to item.id == 1 || true
                        if (results.length > 0) {
                            message = 'Results (vulnerable mode):<br>' + results.map(item => `ID: ${item.id}, Name: ${item.name}`).join('<br>');
                        } else {
                            message = '<p class="error">No results found (vulnerable mode).</p>';
                        }
                    } catch (error) {
                        message = '<p class="error">Error in vulnerable mode: Invalid input caused a failure (e.g., potential injection attempt).</p>';
                    }
                } else if (mode === 'safe') {
                    // Safe mode: Parameterized filtering - Treat input as data only
                    const safeValue = parseFloat(input);  // Parse as a number for ID search
                    if (!isNaN(safeValue)) {
                        results = database.filter(item => item.id === safeValue);  // Exact match on ID
                        if (results.length > 0) {
                            message = 'Results (safe mode):<br>' + results.map(item => `ID: ${item.id}, Name: ${item.name}`).join('<br>');
                        } else {
                            message = '<p class="error">No results found (safe mode).</p>';
                        }
                    } else {
                        message = '<p class="error">Invalid input for safe mode: Please enter a number (e.g., 1).</p>';
                    }
                }

                resultsText.innerHTML = message;
            });
        </script>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
