        <h2>Discussion: Advantages and Disadvantages of the Singleton Pattern</h2>

        <p><strong>Advantages of Singletons:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Global Access and Control:</strong> Singletons provide a single point of access to an instance, making it easy to manage shared resources like the theme state in this example. This ensures consistency across the application without needing to pass the instance around.</li>
            <li><strong>Resource Efficiency:</strong> They can help conserve resources by limiting the creation of multiple instances, which is useful for scenarios involving expensive operations or limited resources (e.g., database connections).</li>
            <li><strong>Simplicity in Small Applications:</strong> For simple projects like this theme manager, Singletons simplify code by avoiding the need for complex dependency management.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Disadvantages of Singletons:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Global State Issues:</strong> Singletons introduce global state, which can make code harder to test, debug, and maintain. For instance, in this demo, the theme state is globally accessible, potentially leading to unintended side effects if the application grows.</li>
            <li><strong>Tight Coupling:</strong> They can create dependencies that make the code less modular and more rigid. If multiple parts of the application rely on the Singleton, changes to it could break other components.</li>
            <li><strong>Testing Challenges:</strong> It's difficult to mock or replace a Singleton for unit testing, as the instance is shared. This can lead to brittle tests that don't isolate components effectively.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>When to Use Dependency Injection or Alternative Patterns:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Dependency Injection (DI):</strong> DI is more appropriate for larger applications where flexibility is key. Instead of a global Singleton, you could inject the theme manager as a dependency into components that need it. This improves testability (e.g., by swapping in mock objects) and modularity. For example, in a framework like Angular or React, you could use providers or context to pass the theme state without global access.</li>
            <li><strong>Alternative Patterns:</strong> Consider using the Factory pattern for creating theme instances if you need more control over instantiation. Or, for state management, patterns like the Observer or State pattern (e.g., via Redux in JavaScript apps) could be better, as they allow for more dynamic and observable state changes without global reliance. Use these alternatives when your application requires scalability, easier testing, or when avoiding global state is important, such as in microservices or modular web apps.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>In summary, while Singletons work well for this simple theme toggle demo, they should be used cautiously in more complex scenarios to avoid common pitfalls.</p>
    </div>

    <script>
        // Singleton ThemeManager class
        class ThemeManager {
            static instance = null; // Static property to hold the single instance

            constructor() {
                if (ThemeManager.instance) {
                    return ThemeManager.instance; // Return existing instance if it exists
                }
                this.theme = 'light'; // Default theme
                ThemeManager.instance = this; // Set the instance
            }

            static getInstance() {
                if (!ThemeManager.instance) {
                    ThemeManager.instance = new ThemeManager(); // Create instance if it doesn't exist
                }
                return ThemeManager.instance;
            }

            toggleTheme() {
                // Toggle the theme state
